00:05:55,080 --> 00:05:59,060
 So that's gonna go descending, doot, doot, doot, doot, doot.

129
00:05:59,060 --> 00:06:02,040
 Sally, Kristen, Colleen, Charles, down they go.

130
00:06:02,040 --> 00:06:02,880
 So that's it.

131
00:06:02,880 --> 00:06:04,680
 Now, we can drop table users.

132
00:06:04,680 --> 00:06:07,020
 And so this is basically the CRUD.

133
00:06:07,020 --> 00:06:11,640
 Insert, CRUD is create, read, update, delete.

134
00:06:11,640 --> 00:06:15,640
 Here it would be insert, select, update, delete.

135
00:06:15,640 --> 00:06:18,320
 But CRUD is sort of kind of the classic concept.

136
00:06:18,320 --> 00:06:22,480
 So we can drop this table users, but how about I do this?

137
00:06:22,480 --> 00:06:25,960
 Let me show you this, what happens if I say

138
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:28,400
 update user set name equals Charles.

139
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:30,800
 Implied in each one of these SQL statements

140
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:33,320
 is it applies to all of them.

141
00:06:33,320 --> 00:06:35,520
 So we got all these records.

142
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:39,860
 Update user set name equals Charles without a where clause.

143
00:06:39,860 --> 00:06:42,520
 And then I say select star from users.

144
00:06:42,520 --> 00:06:45,240
 And you think, oh, that, it did exactly what we told us.

145
00:06:45,240 --> 00:06:48,300
 We didn't say where clause, right?

146
00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:51,000
 You know, that means all the records are affected.

147
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:55,760
 So this update users sort of implies all of the records.

148
00:06:55,760 --> 00:06:59,560
 Now, if we say delete from users

149
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:01,720
 and then don't put a where clause there,

150
00:07:01,720 --> 00:07:03,920
 you're gonna see what happens.

151
00:07:03,920 --> 00:07:06,000
 Delete from users, no where clause.

152
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:08,880
 Implied all of the rows.

153
00:07:08,880 --> 00:07:11,820
 And now I do a select and there is nothing.

154
00:07:11,820 --> 00:07:15,780
 So that's why these where clauses are so important

155
00:07:15,780 --> 00:07:18,960
 on like updates and deletes just so that we know

156
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:20,760
 what rows they're supposed to apply to

157
00:07:20,760 --> 00:07:23,460
 'cause by default they apply to all rows.

158
00:07:23,460 --> 00:07:25,160
 That's why you don't see loops in SQL

159
00:07:25,160 --> 00:07:28,780
 because every statement like the update,

160
00:07:28,780 --> 00:07:31,980
 the select and the delete, they're kind of loops

161
00:07:31,980 --> 00:07:34,180
 automatically and you have to sort of shut them down

162
00:07:34,180 --> 00:07:37,680
 with an if statement as it were, which is that where clause.

163
00:07:37,680 --> 00:07:40,000
 And the last thing we can get is we can drop,

164
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:41,040
 we can just get rid of the table.

165
00:07:41,040 --> 00:07:43,040
 That's another SQL statement.

166
00:07:43,040 --> 00:07:45,760
 If we look at .tables, we see we have one

167
00:07:45,760 --> 00:07:49,080
 and then we say drop table users, put a semicolon there

168
00:07:49,080 --> 00:07:53,940
 and then say .tables and there are no tables left.

169
00:07:53,940 --> 00:07:55,160
 And then I say .quit.

170
00:07:55,160 --> 00:08:00,000
 And now I've got this file called zip.sqlite3

171
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,760
 and I can get rid of it without hurting,

172
00:08:02,760 --> 00:08:05,480
 this is just, this isn't a database that's running

173
00:08:05,480 --> 00:08:08,560
 with a server or anything makes any difference.

174
